<paragraph id="7C756D6F2139F41FFCD90A43FE37B031" blockId="7.[826,1146,1881,1903]" lastBlockId="8.[144,759,198,373]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="875" pageId="7" pageNumber="874">
<emphasis id="4EBEB17D2139F410FCD90A43FC6FB62A" box="[826,996,1881,1902]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="874">Measurements:</emphasis>
See 
<tableCitation id="314858D42139F410FBC30A43FBFEB62A" box="[1056,1141,1881,1903]" captionStart="Table 1" captionStartId="4.[144,208,1627,1646]" captionText="Table 1. Dental measurement of Bardalestes hunco gen. et sp. nov., Bardalestessp., and Riolestes capricornicus gen. et sp. nov. Measurements are in mm" pageId="7" pageNumber="874">Table 1</tableCitation>
. 
<emphasis id="4EBEB17D2136F41FFF730DDCFE8DB19F" box="[144,262,198,219]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="875">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
Differs from the remaining 
<taxonomicName id="BBCA16EC2136F41FFDB40DDCFF36B1BE" authorityName="AMEGHINO" authorityYear="1894" class="Mammalia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Paucituberculata" pageId="8" pageNumber="875" phylum="Chordata" rank="order">Paucituberculata</taxonomicName>
in the following combination of characters: large size, m1 with reduced paraconid, mesially placed; persistence of the paracristid notch, vestigial anterobasal cingulum, trigonid basin absent; metaconid well displaced posteriorly.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7C756D6F2136F41FFF730C87FDB0B4C1" blockId="8.[144,759,412,1413]" pageId="8" pageNumber="875">
<emphasis id="4EBEB17D2136F41FFF730C87FE93B0F6" box="[144,280,413,434]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="875">Description:</emphasis>
The most distinctive features of this molar are its proportionally large size, reduced paraconid, high protoconid, backwardly placed metaconid, absent trigonid basin, labially salient hypoconid (i.e. laterally expanded), and wide talonid basin. The paraconid is poorly developed, much less than the metaconid; its anterior face is flat. The anterobasal cingulum, although vestigial, runs at a short distance below and labial to the paraconid. The metaconid is moderately developed and is set close to the protoconid but quite posterior to it. Thus, the metacristid (postprotocristid + postmetacristid) is short, high, and in occlusal view is obliquely placed with respect to the dental axis. The paracristid (preprotocristid + postparacristid) is sharp, trenchant, and runs steeply downwards, almost subvertical, from the protoconid to the paraconid. The paracristid notch is placed just posterior to the paraconid. The talonid is much wider than the trigonid; its basin is well bound by the pre-entocristid, the cristid oblique, and the posthypocristid. The hypoconid and the entoconid are subequal in height, the latter being laterally compressed; the hypoconulid is located posterolingually relative to the entoconid, and is projected backwards. The cristid obliqua reaches anteriorly up to a point below the notch of the metacristid; it is not parallel to the labial face of the tooth but instead narrows the talonid basin anteriorly. There is no postcingulum. Below the crown, the anterior root is smaller than the posterior one. The cristid obliqua is worn on its anterodorsal edge, as well as the posthypocristid near the hypoconulid and the entoconid at its labial face.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7C756D6F2136F41FFF7308B7FE7DB656" blockId="8.[144,759,1452,1903]" pageId="8" pageNumber="875">
<emphasis id="4EBEB17D2136F41FFF7308B7FD95B486" box="[144,542,1452,1474]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="875">
Comments: 
<taxonomicName id="BBCA16EC2136F41FFEFB08B6FD95B486" authorityName="Goin &amp; Candela &amp; Abello &amp; Oliveira" authorityYear="2009" box="[280,542,1452,1474]" class="Mammalia" family="Paucituberculata incertae sedis" genus="Riolestes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Paucituberculata" pageId="8" pageNumber="875" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="capricornicus">Riolestes capricornicus</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
can be considered a marsupial on the basis of the pairing of the entoconid and the hypoconulid. Its most distinctive features agree well with those expected for a member of the 
<taxonomicName id="BBCA16EC2136F41FFF250B3DFE06B779" authorityName="AMEGHINO" authorityYear="1894" box="[198,397,1575,1597]" class="Mammalia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Paucituberculata" pageId="8" pageNumber="875" phylum="Chordata" rank="order">Paucituberculata</taxonomicName>
: labially projected hypoconid and laterally compressed entoconid (see below). An additional feature, the metaconid clearly posterior to the protoconid, occurs in the first molar in most 
<taxonomicName id="BBCA16EC2136F41FFF380BBBFE14B7F3" authorityName="AMEGHINO" authorityYear="1894" box="[219,415,1697,1719]" class="Mammalia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Paucituberculata" pageId="8" pageNumber="875" phylum="Chordata" rank="order">Paucituberculata</taxonomicName>
– except in 
<taxonomicName id="BBCA16EC2136F41FFDBC0BBBFD64B7F2" authorityName="Ameghino" authorityYear="1887" box="[607,751,1697,1718]" class="Mammalia" family="Caenolestidae" genus="Stilotherium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Paucituberculata" pageId="8" pageNumber="875" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="4EBEB17D2136F41FFDBC0BBBFD64B7F2" box="[607,751,1697,1718]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="875">Stilotherium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="BBCA16EC2136F41FFF730BDAFEB3B791" authorityName="Ameghino" authorityYear="1894" box="[144,312,1728,1749]" class="Mammalia" family="Caenolestidae" genus="Phonocdromus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Paucituberculata" pageId="8" pageNumber="875" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="4EBEB17D2136F41FFF730BDAFEB3B791" box="[144,312,1728,1749]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="875">Phonocdromus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="BBCA16EC2136F41FFE9A0BDAFE67B791" authorityName="Ameghino" authorityYear="1890" box="[377,492,1728,1749]" class="Mammalia" family="Caenolestidae" genus="Pichipilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Paucituberculata" pageId="8" pageNumber="875" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="4EBEB17D2136F41FFE9A0BDAFE67B791" box="[377,492,1728,1749]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="875">Pichipilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Finally, the paraconid of m1 is reduced in all paucituberculatans, as in the 
<typeStatus id="A371D3CD2136F41FFF730BE7FF4AB656" box="[144,193,1789,1810]" pageId="8" pageNumber="875">type</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName id="BBCA16EC2136F41FFF0A0BE7FE64B657" authorityName="Goin &amp; Candela &amp; Abello &amp; Oliveira" authorityYear="2009" box="[233,495,1789,1811]" class="Mammalia" family="Paucituberculata incertae sedis" genus="Riolestes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Paucituberculata" pageId="8" pageNumber="875" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="capricornicus">
<emphasis id="4EBEB17D2136F41FFF0A0BE7FE64B657" box="[233,495,1789,1811]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="875">Riolestes capricornicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7C756D6F2136F41FFF4B0A06FB81B4A5" blockId="8.[144,759,1452,1903]" lastBlockId="8.[806,1422,198,1903]" pageId="8" pageNumber="875">
Although not frequent among more modern marsupials, the location of the metaconid somewhat posterior with respect to the protoconid appears not only in the m1 but also in the dp3s of several different lineages, including some very generalized forms such as 
<taxonomicName id="BBCA16EC2136F41FFC3B0C19FBCCB05C" authorityName="Simpson" authorityYear="1927" box="[984,1095,259,280]" class="Mammalia" family="Didelphidae" genus="Alphadon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Didelphimorphia" pageId="8" pageNumber="875" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="4EBEB17D2136F41FFC3B0C19FBCCB05C" box="[984,1095,259,280]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="875">Alphadon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation id="185B109E2136F41FFBB90C19FB7EB05D" author="Cifelli RL" box="[1114,1269,259,281]" pageId="8" pageNumber="875" pagination="117 - 136" refId="ref10942" refString="Cifelli RL. 1994. Therian mammals of the terlingua local fauna (Judithian), Aguja formation, big bend of the Rio Grande, Texas. Contributions to Geology, University of Wyoming 30: 117 - 136." type="journal article" year="1994">Cifelli (1994)</bibRefCitation>
, referring to several deciduous molars tentatively referred to 
<taxonomicName id="BBCA16EC2136F41FFCC50C5AFB92B012" authorityName="Cifelli" authorityYear="1994" box="[806,1049,320,342]" class="Mammalia" family="Didelphidae" genus="Alphadon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Didelphimorphia" pageId="8" pageNumber="875" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="perexiguus">
<emphasis id="4EBEB17D2136F41FFCC50C5AFB92B012" box="[806,1049,320,342]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="875">Alphadon perexiguus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, pointed out that ‘... the trigonid is broadly open lingually, with the paraconid and metaconid more anteriorly and posteriorly placed, respectively, than on the permanent molars. The paraconid and metaconid are weakly developed (...) As usual among marsupial dP3s, the cristid obliqua extends anterolingually as a crest to the tip of the metaconid, resembling the distal metacristid (...) seen in permanent molars of primitive Tribosphenida’ (
<bibRefCitation id="185B109E2136F41FFC5D0F4EFB00B32D" author="Cifelli RL" box="[958,1163,596,618]" pageId="8" pageNumber="875" pagination="117 - 136" refId="ref10942" refString="Cifelli RL. 1994. Therian mammals of the terlingua local fauna (Judithian), Aguja formation, big bend of the Rio Grande, Texas. Contributions to Geology, University of Wyoming 30: 117 - 136." type="journal article" year="1994">Cifelli, 1994: 124</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="185B109E2136F41FFB780F4EFCEBB3CC" author="Cifelli RL &amp; de Muizon C" pageId="8" pageNumber="875" pagination="532 - 537" refId="ref10983" refString="Cifelli RL, de Muizon C. 1998. Marsupial mammals from the upper Cretaceous North Horn Formation, Central Utah. Journal of Paleontology 72: 532 - 537." type="journal article" year="1998">Cifelli &amp; de Muizon, 1998</bibRefCitation>
). The posterior placement of the metaconid with respect to the protoconid is also verified in the permanent molars of some Early Palaeocene South American taxa, such as the polydolopimorphian 
<emphasis id="4EBEB17D2136F41FFABA0FD4FB3DB246" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="875">Roberthofftetteria nationalgeographica</emphasis>
. Among the most primitive 
<taxonomicName id="BBCA16EC2136F41FFC7F0E11FBCDB265" box="[924,1094,779,801]" class="Mammalia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sparassodonta" pageId="8" pageNumber="875" phylum="Chordata" rank="order">Sparassodonta</taxonomicName>
, such as some 
<taxonomicName id="BBCA16EC2136F41FFAE50E11FCD3B204" baseAuthorityName="Ameghino" baseAuthorityYear="1894" class="Mammalia" family="Hathliacynidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sparassodonta" pageId="8" pageNumber="875" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Hathliacynidae</taxonomicName>
, the reduction of the metaconid in m1 occurs together with its posterior placement in the trigonid. In some 
<taxonomicName id="BBCA16EC2136F41FFC310E7DFB14B239" authorityName="Ameghino" authorityYear="1887" box="[978,1183,871,893]" class="Mammalia" family="Microbiotheriidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Microbiotheria" pageId="8" pageNumber="875" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Microbiotheriidae</taxonomicName>
, such as 
<taxonomicName id="BBCA16EC2136F41FFAFD0E7DFB87B2DF" authorityName="Ameghino" authorityYear="1902" class="Mammalia" family="Didelphidae" genus="Pachybiotherium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Didelphimorphia" pageId="8" pageNumber="875" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="acclinum">
<emphasis id="4EBEB17D2136F41FFAFD0E7DFB87B2DF" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="875">Pachybiotherium acclinum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="BBCA16EC2136F41FFBD40E9CFA0DB2DF" box="[1079,1414,902,923]" class="Mammalia" family="Microbiotheriidae" genus="Eomicrobiotherium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Microbiotheria" pageId="8" pageNumber="875" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="gaudry">
<emphasis id="4EBEB17D2136F41FFBD40E9CFA0DB2DF" box="[1079,1414,902,923]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="875">Eomicrobiotherium gaudry</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="BBCA16EC2136F41FFC870EBEFB4AB2FD" authorityName="Sinclair" authorityYear="1906" box="[868,1217,932,953]" class="Mammalia" family="Microbiotheriidae" genus="Microbiotherium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Microbiotheria" pageId="8" pageNumber="875" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="gallegosense">
<emphasis id="4EBEB17D2136F41FFC870EBEFB4AB2FD" box="[868,1217,932,953]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="875">Microbiotherium gallegosense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the posteriorly ‘shifted’ metaconid in m1 occurs together with the mesial ‘shift’ of the paraconid, as in 
<taxonomicName id="BBCA16EC2136F41FFB390EFBFAB6B2B2" authorityName="Goin &amp; Candela &amp; Abello &amp; Oliveira" authorityYear="2009" box="[1242,1341,993,1014]" class="Mammalia" family="Paucituberculata incertae sedis" genus="Riolestes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Paucituberculata" pageId="8" pageNumber="875" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="4EBEB17D2136F41FFB390EFBFAB6B2B2" box="[1242,1341,993,1014]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="875">Riolestes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Some early 
<taxonomicName id="BBCA16EC2136F41FFC9A091AFBB5B552" authorityName="Gill" authorityYear="1872" box="[889,1086,1024,1046]" class="Mammalia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Didelphimorphia" pageId="8" pageNumber="875" phylum="Chordata" rank="order">Didelphimorphia</taxonomicName>
, such as 
<taxonomicName id="BBCA16EC2136F41FFB39091AFC09B570" authorityName="Marshall &amp; de Muizon" authorityYear="1984" class="Mammalia" family="Sternbergiidae" genus="Itaboraidelphys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Paucituberculata" pageId="8" pageNumber="875" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="camposi">
<emphasis id="4EBEB17D2136F41FFB39091AFC09B570" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="875">Itaboraidelphys camposi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, also show a slight posterior displacement of the metaconid. Finally, among the 
<taxonomicName id="BBCA16EC2136F41FFB0E0927FCD8B536" authorityName="AMEGHINO" authorityYear="1894" class="Mammalia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Paucituberculata" pageId="8" pageNumber="875" phylum="Chordata" rank="order">Paucituberculata</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicName id="BBCA16EC2136F41FFC830946FB8BB536" authorityName="Trouessart" authorityYear="1898" box="[864,1024,1116,1138]" class="Mammalia" family="Caenolestidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Paucituberculata" pageId="8" pageNumber="875" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Caenolestidae</taxonomicName>
and, especially, 
<taxonomicName id="BBCA16EC2136F41FFB2E0946FA02B536" authorityName="Sinclair" authorityYear="1906" box="[1229,1417,1116,1138]" class="Mammalia" family="Palaeothentidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Paucituberculata" pageId="8" pageNumber="875" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Palaeothentidae</taxonomicName>
, the m1 metaconid also shows a displacement similar to that of 
<taxonomicName id="BBCA16EC2136F41FFC410983FB8EB5EA" authorityName="Goin &amp; Candela &amp; Abello &amp; Oliveira" authorityYear="2009" box="[930,1029,1177,1198]" class="Mammalia" family="Paucituberculata incertae sedis" genus="Riolestes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Paucituberculata" pageId="8" pageNumber="875" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="4EBEB17D2136F41FFC410983FB8EB5EA" box="[930,1029,1177,1198]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="875">Riolestes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In short, the posterior displacement of the metaconid is not exclusive to the marsupial dp3 but also occurs in several permanent molars in various lineages, noticeably in the m1 of most 
<taxonomicName id="BBCA16EC2136F41FFC840809FBA5B46D" authorityName="AMEGHINO" authorityYear="1894" box="[871,1070,1299,1321]" class="Mammalia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Paucituberculata" pageId="8" pageNumber="875" phylum="Chordata" rank="order">Paucituberculata</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation id="185B109E2136F41FFBDF0809FAC1B46D" author="Luckett WP &amp; Hong N" box="[1084,1354,1299,1321]" pageId="8" pageNumber="875" pagination="109 - 127" refId="ref11932" refString="Luckett WP, Hong N. 2000. Ontogenetic evidence for dental homologies and premolar replacement in fossil and extant caenolestids (Marsupialia). Journal of Mammalian Evolution 7: 109 - 127." type="journal article" year="2000">Luckett &amp; Hong (2000)</bibRefCitation>
demonstrated that the dp3 is vestigial and extremely reduced in paucituberculatans, which is obviously not the case in MCN-PV 1790. Finally, the positions and relative sizes of the trigonid cusps in 
<taxonomicName id="BBCA16EC2136F41FFAC90894FC34B486" authorityName="Goin &amp; Candela &amp; Abello &amp; Oliveira" authorityYear="2009" class="Mammalia" family="Paucituberculata incertae sedis" genus="Riolestes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Paucituberculata" pageId="8" pageNumber="875" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="capricornicus">
<emphasis id="4EBEB17D2136F41FFAC90894FC34B486" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="875">Riolestes capricornicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
match well those of the m1 of paucituberculatans.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7C756D6F2136F41FFCDC08F3FC2DB62A" blockId="8.[806,1422,198,1903]" pageId="8" pageNumber="875">
<taxonomicName id="BBCA16EC2136F41FFCDC08F3FBC0B4BB" authorityName="Goin &amp; Candela &amp; Abello &amp; Oliveira" authorityYear="2009" box="[831,1099,1513,1535]" class="Mammalia" family="Paucituberculata incertae sedis" genus="Riolestes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Paucituberculata" pageId="8" pageNumber="875" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="capricornicus">
<emphasis id="4EBEB17D2136F41FFCDC08F3FBC0B4BB" box="[831,1099,1513,1535]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="875">Riolestes capricornicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="BBCA16EC2136F41FFB7708F3FAC3B4BB" box="[1172,1352,1513,1535]" class="Mammalia" family="Paucituberculata incertae sedis" genus="Bardalestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Paucituberculata" pageId="8" pageNumber="875" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="4EBEB17D2136F41FFB7708F3FA92B4BA" box="[1172,1305,1513,1534]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="875">Bardalestes</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
from Las 
<collectingCountry id="04DD2DFF2136F41FFCB40B12FC15B75A" box="[855,926,1544,1566]" name="Indonesia" pageId="8" pageNumber="875">Flores</collectingCountry>
are contemporary paucituberculatans. Differences between them include the following features: 
<taxonomicName id="BBCA16EC2136F41FFCC50B5FFBA0B71F" authorityName="Goin &amp; Candela &amp; Abello &amp; Oliveira" authorityYear="2009" box="[806,1067,1605,1627]" class="Mammalia" family="Paucituberculata incertae sedis" genus="Riolestes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Paucituberculata" pageId="8" pageNumber="875" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="capricornicus">
<emphasis id="4EBEB17D2136F41FFCC50B5FFBA0B71F" box="[806,1067,1605,1627]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="875">Riolestes capricornicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
triples 
<taxonomicName id="BBCA16EC2136F41FFB650B5FFAB8B71F" box="[1158,1331,1605,1627]" class="Mammalia" family="Paucituberculata incertae sedis" genus="Bardalestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Paucituberculata" pageId="8" pageNumber="875" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="4EBEB17D2136F41FFB650B5FFA80B71E" box="[1158,1291,1605,1626]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="875">Bardalestes</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
in size; its 
<typeStatus id="A371D3CD2136F41FFCB40B7EFC03B73D" box="[855,904,1636,1657]" pageId="8" pageNumber="875">type</typeStatus>
specimen differs from the lower molar referred to 
<taxonomicName id="BBCA16EC2136F41FFC560B98FBE3B7DC" box="[949,1128,1666,1688]" class="Mammalia" family="Paucituberculata incertae sedis" genus="Bardalestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Paucituberculata" pageId="8" pageNumber="875" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="4EBEB17D2136F41FFC560B98FBB1B7D3" box="[949,1082,1666,1687]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="875">Bardalestes</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
in that there is a less salient hypoconid, the entoconid is comparatively smaller, the hypoconulid is less proximate to the entoconid (in 
<taxonomicName id="BBCA16EC2136F41FFC2C0BC4FBDFB7B7" authorityName="Goin &amp; Candela &amp; Abello &amp; Oliveira" authorityYear="2009" box="[975,1108,1758,1779]" class="Mammalia" family="Paucituberculata incertae sedis" genus="Bardalestes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Paucituberculata" pageId="8" pageNumber="875" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="4EBEB17D2136F41FFC2C0BC4FBDFB7B7" box="[975,1108,1758,1779]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="875">Bardalestes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it is almost immediately posterior to the entoconid), it has a shallower talonid basin, and it lacks a posterobasal cingulum. All these differences warrant a generic distinction between these taxa.
</paragraph>
